put your private key here

make sure to set permissions to 600 (chmod 600 id_ed25519)

generate a new dedicated key with `ssh-keygen -t ed25519 -f ./id_ed25519` if you
don't have one yet, and add the PUBLIC key (id_ed25519.pub) to the remote
tunnel user's `~/.ssh/authorized_keys` file.

Use a dedicated, locked-down user on the remote (not root), and restrict that
user's authorized_keys entry with:
  command="echo 'no shell access, tunnel only'",no-agent-forwarding,no-X11-forwarding,no-pty
so the key can only be used to establish the tunnel, not to get a shell.